uries it has proven to be a stimulus for art and literature.Toohey shows that boredom is a universal emotion experienced by humans throughout history and he explains its place, and value, in today's world. Boredom: A Lively History is vital reading for anyone interested in what goes on when supposedly nothing happens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Emotions.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030014110840uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030017216440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300172164423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300172164/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY